<paragraph blockId="35.[151,573,726,786]" box="[151,384,761,786]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">(Figs. 13.8 and 26.3)</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1436,833,966]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
Caatinga endemic species. It is known only for the state of Bahia, municipalities of Barra and Pilão Arcado, on depositional lowlands from 
<quantity box="[463,611,869,894]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="4.06" metricValueMin="3.94" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" unit="m" value="400.0" valueMax="406.0" valueMin="394.0">394 to 406 m</quantity>
elevation, close to the eastern banks of the São Francisco river channel. It was recorded only in bushy and herbaceous caatinga on dunes and sandy soil (
<bibRefCitation author="Rodrigues" box="[1023,1206,905,930]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" refString="Rodrigues, M. T. (1992) Herpetofauna das dunas interiores do Rio Sao Francisco: Bahia: Brasil. V. Duas novas especies de Apostolepis (Ophidia, Colubridae). Memorias do Instituto Butantan, 54, 53 - 59." type="journal article" year="1992">
Rodrigues 
<number box="[1146,1206,906,930]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" value="1992.0">1992</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). It has fossorial and psammophylous habits, is diurnal and nocturnal, and feeds on elongated vertebrates (
<bibRefCitation author="Ferrarezzi" box="[1103,1349,941,966]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" refString="Ferrarezzi, H., Barbo, F. E. &amp; Albuquerque, C. E. (2005) Phylogenetic relationships of a new species of Apostolepis from Brazilian cerrado with notes on the assimilis group (Serpentes: Colubridae: Xenodontinae: Elapomorphini). Papeis Avulsos de Zoologia, 45, 215 - 229. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1590 / S 0031 - 10492005001600001" type="journal article" year="2005">
Ferrarezzi 
<emphasis box="[1225,1282,941,966]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[1288,1349,941,966]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" value="2005.0">2005</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
